{"key":"processedPost-14993826","value":{"id":14993826,"first":14967890,"last":14997303,"when":1314589469,"utime":"08/29/11 06:44 AM","cleanedPost":"The only thing that's really changed is the nomenclature.&nbsp; Coir was used a lot as a 'casing layer' in years past and it always fruited well.&nbsp; Coir/verm is especially good.&nbsp; However, since coir has lots of food for mycelium, it's not really a casing material, but rather a bulk substrate material.&nbsp; The thing to remember is that cubensis doesn't require a casing, fruiting very well from uncased bulk substrates, which is what you really have when using coir.<br />I hope that makes sense.&nbsp; I've explained it better elsewhere.<br />RR"}}